briefdescription.para: Macro used to indicate a function takes a printf-like specification.

detaileddescription.para: This attribute is used as follows: voidPrintFunc(T1arg1,T2arg2,constchar*fmt,...) ARCH_PRINTF_FUNCTION(3,4) This indicates that the third argument is the format string, and that the fourth argument is where the var-args corresponding to the format string begin.

briefdescription.para: Macro used to indicate a function takes a scanf-like specification.

detaileddescription.para: This attribute is used as follows: voidScanFunc(T1arg1,T2arg2,constchar*fmt,...) ARCH_PRINTF_FUNCTION(3,4) This indicates that the third argument is the format string, and that the fourth argument is where the var-args corresponding to the format string begin.

briefdescription.para: Macro used to indicate that a function should never be inlined.

detaileddescription.para: This attribute is used as follows: voidFunc(T1arg1,T2arg2)ARCH_NOINLINE;

briefdescription.para: Macro used to indicate a function parameter may be unused.
Macro used to indicate a function may be unused.
Macro used to indicate that a function's code must always be emitted even if not required.

detaileddescription.para: This attribute is especially useful with templated registration functions, which might not be present in the linked binary if they are not used (or the compiler optimizes away their use.)

briefdescription.para: Macro to begin the definition of a function that should be executed by the dynamic loader when the dynamic object (library or program) is loaded.

detaileddescription.para: _priority is used to order the execution of constructors. Valid values are integers in the range [0,255]. Constructors with lower numbers are run first. It is unspecified if these functions are run before or after dynamic initialization of non-local variables.

_name is the name of the function and must be unique across all invocations of ARCH_CONSTRUCTOR in the same translation unit. The remaining arguments should be types for the signature of the function. The types are only to make the name unique (when mangled); the function will be called with no arguments so the arguments must not be used. If you don't need any arguments you must use void.

briefdescription.para: Macro to begin the definition of a function that should be executed by the dynamic loader when the dynamic object (library or program) is unloaded.

detaileddescription.para: _priority is used to order the execution of destructors. Valid values are integers in the range [0,255]. Destructors with higher numbers are run first. It is unspecified if these functions are run before or after dynamically initialized non-local variables.

_name is the name of the function and must be unique across all invocations of ARCH_CONSTRUCTOR in the same translation unit. The remaining arguments should be types for the signature of the function. The types are only to make the name unique (when mangled); the function will be called with no arguments so the arguments must not be used. If you don't need any arguments you must use void.

briefdescription.para: Macro to begin the definition of a class that is using private inheritance to take advantage of the empty base optimization.

detaileddescription.para: Some compilers require an explicit tag.
In C++20, usage of private inheritance may be able to be retired with the [[no_unique_address]] tag.
This file allows you to define architecture-specific or compiler-specific options to be used outside lib/arch.
